observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendations that the Local Chief Executive, through its Municipal Human Resource Management Officer to:
a. setup policy guidelines to address the issues on the necessity and propriety of hiring job orders in order to limit the expenditures to programs/projects that are highly essential to merit the recruitment of the same;
b. hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months;
c. comply with submission of Daily Time Records and Accomplishment Reports with specific output to evaluate the necessity and validity of all JO personnel employed; and
d. rationalize the daily rates of job-order personnel based on qualifications and skillset.
Further, we recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the:
a. Municipal Budget Officer to regularly update the RAAO to facilitate the preparation of the monthly list of signed and issued Obligation Requests with complete information such as ObR control number, name of payee, particulars/nature of transaction, amount, Function/Program/ Project (FPP), complete budget name, name of responsibility center, date signed and account code, and furnish the same to the Audit Team Leader for audit and monitoring purposes;
b. Municipal Accountant and its Supervising Officer to ensure that disbursement vouchers for payment of JO wages are supported with monthly Daily Time Records and Accomplishment Report with specific output certified correct by the assigned authority/head;
c. Municipal Treasurer ensure that claims for payment are duly signed by the JO personnel and/or authorization letter in case the claimant is other than the JO.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require instruct the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit 

CY 2020 Bank Reconciliation Statements on all bank accounts; 
adjusting entries with supporting documents based on the results of the Bank Reconciliation Statements; 
CY 2020 Financial Statements ending December 2020; 
CY 2020 Subsidiary and General Ledgers tallied with journals, adjusting entries and working Trial Balance ending December 2020; 
adjusting entries on unrecorded PPE totaling ₱53,387,661.09 and maintain detailed description of mentioned properties; and 
Lapsing Schedule of Depreciation and draw an adjusting entry to record depreciation for CYs 2019 and 2020.

We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant to investigate the debit balances in the Liabilities accounts and prepare adjusting entries based on the results of the investigation, if needed.

Henceforth, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

Municipal Budget Officer   to set-aside budget for the trainings of accounting personnel, mostly newly-hired accounting staff, especially in Government Accounting Manuals for LGUs; and 

Municipal Accountant to (i) improve supervisory and review controls in the recognition of transactions and preparation of financial statements to prevent the accumulation of errors and misstatements in the Financial Statements; (ii) start maintaining subsidiary and general ledgers; and (iii) always prepare Bank Reconciliation Statements and Lapsing Schedule of Depreciation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

Municipal Accountant to (i) address the backlog on the preparation and submission of BRS; and (ii) make the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts of the unrecorded debit and credit memos and the discrepancies noted in the recording of Cash in Bank transactions; 

 Municipal Treasurer to (i) take efforts that all issued checks for payment of valid obligations be promptly released to the claimants the soonest possible time to prevent checks from becoming stale; (ii) cancel stale checks following the procedures provided for under Section 59 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with other Offices concerned, to

expedite the submission of the documentary deficiencies, including Distribution List or its equivalent of the procured rice and assorted food items, to the Audit Team; 

effect payment only on services rendered and goods delivered, inspected and accepted except for those expressly provided for by regulations; 

work on the immediate liquidation of cash advances as soon as the purposes of the grant have already been served and the submission of the liquidation documents to the Audit Team; and 

ensure the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction and provide all the required data/information before any payment is made.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

MBO to maintain the required registries to prevent incurrence of expenditures in excess of allotments or budget overrun; 

concerned personnel to abide strictly with the COA regulations on the use of motor vehicles and refrain from utilizing government funds for gasoline consumption of privately-owned vehicles to prevent disallowances; and regulate the issuance of serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets duly supported with Purchase Order (PO) to ensure that claims are duly authorized; 

Municipal Accountant to submit copy of the notarized contract with FCC General Merchandise Corp. and Decem Gasoline Station as required under Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular 2009-001; and 

concerned drivers and officials to prepare the Monthly Report of Official Travels and the Report of Fuel Consumption and submit the same to the Auditor for verification to ensure that expenditures for fuel consumption are reasonable, effectively controlled and properly accounted for.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the

Municipal Planning and Development Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Budget Officer, to (i) comply with the reportorial and monitoring requirements as prescribed in DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2008-156 on the submission of Annual/End-of-Term Accomplishment Report for all development projects; 

(ii) along with the LDC, improve the optimization of the 20% Development Fund thru in-depth planning to ensure that only programs and projects geared towards the attainment of socio-economic and environmental management outcomes that partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures will be given allocation under the Fund; and 

(iii) avoid implementing generic/lump-sum projects in the Fund without authority from the Sanggunian;  

Municipal Budget Officer to (i) maintain and regularly update the RAAO for the 20% DF as basis for the preparation of the monitoring and evaluation reports for all the 20% DF projects;

 (ii) refrain from charging ineligible PPAs not specifically found in the 20% DF investment program and not included in the appropriations for allowable development projects; and 

 Municipal Accountant to comply with the accrual basis of accounting in financial reporting and ensure that expenditures which could not be paid in the current year be recognized as Accounts Payable at the year-end.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the 

MBO to (i) adequately appropriate in its annual budget no less than five percent (5%) of the estimated revenue from regular sources as LDRRMF; and 

(ii) maintain a separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for LDRRMF pursuant to Item 5.1.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; 

MDRRM Officer to (i) prepare the Annual LDRRM Investment Plan and subject to further amendments, if the need arises, particularly in the case of public health threats, and certification as to availability of funds duly certified by the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant prior to funding of such PPAs; 

(ii) prepare the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-002; and 

(iii) refrain from charging ineligible expenditures classified as regular operating expenses to the LDRRMF and ensure that funds are used in accordance with Section 21 of R.A. No. 10121 and Item 4.3 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2014-1;   

Municipal Accountant, MBO and Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with one another to establish the remaining unutilized balance of the LDDRMF based on the realized income from regular sources and compute for the unutilized balance backed up by cash for transfer to the special trust fund; and 

 Municipal Accountant to (i) fully disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the details of the unexpended LDRRMF balance of previous years which accrued to the special trust fund under the account “Trust Liability-DRRM” and maintain the subsidiary ledgers thereon; 

(ii) verify the validity and completeness of supporting documents of DVs before payment is made; and 

(iii) work on the immediate liquidation of cash advances as soon as the purposes of the grant had already been served.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

(a) Municipal Budget Officer to fully accomplish all entries in the Obligation Requests (ObR) and regularly update the RAAO to facilitate the preparation of monthly list of signed and issued Obligation Requests with information such as ObR control number, name of payee, particulars/nature of transaction, amount, Function/Program/ Project (FPP), complete budget name, name of responsibility center, date signed and account code, for submission to the Audit Team Leader for audit and monitoring purposes; 

(b) Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursement vouchers for processing and payment are supported with duly accomplished Obligation Request such as FPP per approved appropriation, account code, and signature of requestor on the certification of charges to appropriation/allotment necessary, lawful and under direct supervision portion of ObR especially payroll transactions;  

(c) Municipal Treasurer to ensure that claims for payment are duly supported with the necessary documents, including the duly accomplished ObR and the signature of the requestor; and 

(d) Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to support and coordinate with each other in the preparation of the complete Registries of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) and Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances (SAAOB) for CY 2017 to be used in the presentation of Statement of Comparative Budget and Actual Amount in the CY 2017 Financial Statements, and every accounting period thereafter.

(e) institute appropriate administrative sanctions against the erring official/s concerned for habitual neglect of duty if no significant improvement is evident in the financial and budgetary reporting of the Municipality after a reasonable period.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the  

(a) Municipal Budget Officer to (i) accomplish separate RAAO for 20% DF and (ii) refrain from charging projects, programs and activities against the budget without the covering appropriation; and (iii) make the proper coordination with the Sanggunian Bayan in reviewing the approved budget components of the Municipality;  

(b) Acting Municipal Accountant, along with other concerned officials to (i) check adequacy of the documentary requirements to establish regularity of claims by referring to COA Circular No. 2012-001 and the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and other relevant memoranda; and (ii) strengthen the controls in the handling and recording procedures of accounting transactions; 


(c) Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Officer, to (i) comply with the reportorial and monitoring requirements as prescribed in the COA Circular 2013-004 on submission of comprehensive Quarterly Report of the Publicized Government Projects/ Programs/Activities on Goods and Infrastructures and to accomplish ; (ii) render report on Annual Accomplishment Report (Form 6a) as one of the required forms in the consolidation of Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP) and Local Development Investment Program (LDIP) pursuant to DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2008-156 dated October 22, 2008 in order to improve the level and quality of monitoring on the status of project implementation, including the preparation and submission of regular status reports; and (iii) along with the LDC, improve the optimization of 20% Development Fund thru judicious planning and compliance with the guidelines on the utilization of the DF under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1; and 


(d) BAC and its Secretariat to subject all procurement to public bidding unless the conditions are present for the use of shopping or other alternative mode of procurement and prepare a complete and comprehensive Annual Procurement Plan containing all the requirements of the Municipality within a year using the format prescribed by Section 3.2 of GPPB Circular No. 01-2009 dated January 20, 2009 and pursuant to the Procurement Manual for Local Government Units.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) thru the Focal Person for solid waste management and Environmental Care Management Unit Head 

(a) involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the implementation of the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household and business level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality;  

(b) seek the help of private companies/organizations and schools in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste; 

(c) formulate solid waste management programs that would encourage and motivate the public to give their cooperation and full support; 

(d) assist the Barangays in scouting for suitable land for the establishment of their own MRF; and 

(e) enforce the penalties provided in Municipal Ecological Solid Waste Management Ordinance No. 3 and Segregation at Source Ordinance No. 5 to ensure compliance thereof.

We also recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Budget Officer to provide 

(f) sufficient amount for Information and Education Campaign on Solid Waste Management to raise awareness of people in protecting the environment and in encouraging more ecologically-responsible behavior; and 

(g) as far as the budget may permit, subsidize the acquisition of the land to be purchased for MRF by the barangays in the next budget preparation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
General Services Officer, together with the Inventory Committee, to (i) exert concerted efforts to reconstruct the PPE records including Property Cards and Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment, and (ii) render a reliable and complete report on the physical count of PPE accounts every year and submit the same to the Accounting Office for the reconciliation thereof with the books;
General Services Officer, together with the Divestment and Disposal Committee, to cause the immediate disposal of unserviceable assets following the pertinent guidelines in supply and property management;
Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Assessor to (i) exert efforts in completing the necessary documents to facilitate the transfer of ownership of the real properties in the name of the Municipality; and (ii) come up with fair value of lands owned by the Municipality that have not yet been recognized in the books owing to lack of basis for valuation purposes;
Municipal Accountant to (i) strengthen the controls in the handling and recording procedures affecting PPE accounts; (ii) update/reconstruct PPELC, lapsing schedule and subsidiary records in order to facilitate reconciliation and draw the necessary correcting entries for identified errors and omissions; (iii) improve supervisory and review controls in the recognition of transactions and preparation of financial statements to prevent the accumulation of errors and misstatements in the financial statements; and (iv) effect the necessary correcting entries in the books, if necessary.
The Management mentioned that they would make necessary adjustments at the beginning of CY 2019.  Further, they would submit the basis of the Appraisal Committee on the valuation of equipment and other properties acquired years ago as indicated in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE).

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) address with urgency the issue on lack of competencies in the manpower complement of the Accounting Office; 

(b) reconstitute the Municipality’s Inventory Committee who will be tasked to facilitate the reconstruction of records and to render a reliable and complete report on the physical count of PPE accounts every year and to submit the same to the Accounting Office for the reconciliation thereof with the books; 

(c) instruct the General Services Officer to cause the immediate disposal of unserviceable assets following the pertinent guidelines in supply and property management; 

(d) instruct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Assessor to (i) exert efforts in completing the necessary documents to facilitate the transfer of ownership of the real properties in the name of the Municipality; (ii) come up with fair value of lands owned by the Municipality that have not yet been recognized in the books owing to lack of basis for valuation purposes; 

(e) instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) strengthen the controls in the handling and recording procedures affecting PPE accounts; (ii) update/reconstruct accounting and subsidiary records in order to facilitate reconciliation and draw the necessary correcting entries for identified errors and omissions; (iii) improve supervisory and review controls in the recognition of transactions and preparation of financial statements to prevent the accumulation of errors and misstatements in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the Municipal Assessor to hasten the identification of duplicate records and tax-exempted real property units for adjustment in the Integrated Taxation Management System;

(b) direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare a subsidiary ledger per individual accounts based on the “cleansed” certified list of real property taxpayers as a result of the aforementioned efforts; 

(c) henceforth, regularly reconcile the balance of RPT/SET Receivable account with the list of taxpayers with paid/unpaid real property tax dues maintained by the Municipal Treasurer then draw journal entry vouchers to adjust the balances thereof; and 

(d) continue to coordinate with the system developer to hasten efforts to make the i-Tax system a reliable system.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) abide strictly with the COA regulations on the use of motor vehicles and refrain from utilizing government funds for gasoline consumption of privately-owned vehicles to prevent disallowances; 

(b) assign a point person under the General Services Office who will regulate the issuance of serially numbered Driver’s Trip Tickets duly supported with Purchase Order (PO) to ensure that claims are duly authorized; 

(c) submit a copy of notarized contract with FCC General Merchandise Corp. and Triple V Gasoline as required under Item 3.1.1 of COA Circular 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009; and 

(d) direct the concerned drivers and officials to prepare Monthly Report of Official Travels and the Report of Fuel Consumption and submit the same to the Auditor for verification to ensure that expenditures for fuel consumption are reasonable, effectively controlled and properly accounted for.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

(a) MDRRMO to (i) send formal letter-request to the Office of Civil Defense for the conduct of trainings especially RDANA, MIRA and PDNA; (ii) look for training providers as early as the 2nd quarter of the year to cover the remaining trainings not yet attended by MDRRO personnel; and (iii) submit the final draft of Incident Command System to the Municipal Mayor for her approval to ensure effective management of disasters or emergencies; 

(b) Municipal Budget Officer/Municipal Development Planning Officer to (i) provide 5% of the total budget from regular sources for the Local Disaster Risk Reduction Management Fund pursuant to Section 21 of R.A. No. 10121; (ii) maintain a separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for LDRRMF pursuant to Item 5.1.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012; and, henceforth, (iii) provide detailed description of trainings/projects in the LDRRMIP; 

(c) BAC and its Secretariat to (i) subject all procurements to public bidding unless the conditions are present for the use of shopping as alternative mode of procurement; (ii) comply strictly with Section 54.1 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184 on the prohibition of splitting of contract; and (b) prepare Annual Procurement Plan containing all the requirements of the Municipality within a year with format as prescribed by Paragraph 3.2 of GPPB Circular No. 01-2009 dated January 20, 2009; and 

(d) Municipal Accountant, in coordination with other offices involved, work on the completion of the documentary deficiencies pertinent to the rental of heavy equipment for the evaluation of the Audit Team as basis for its next audit action.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant (i) comply with the submission of the documentary requirements, as enumerated above (ii) ensure that the required documentary requirements supporting of all purchases especially medicines are present; and (iii) record all purchases of drugs and medicines in the books using the Inventory account and use the Monthly Summary of Medicines Utilized prepared by MHO as basis in recording of utilized medicines in Drugs and Medicines Expense account.

BAC Secretariat submit screenshots of posted notices at PhilGEPS website in CY 2016 (sample shown in Annex B) and give written explanations if the invitation to bid for the procurement of medicines purchased from Ladyjen Medical Trading and RDW Trading was not posted at PhilGEPS website;

Municipal Health Officer (MHO) and BAC Secretariat (i) invariably provide the complete description of medicines in Purchase Request especially the unit of doses in milligram (mg) or volume/weight of bottle or ointment in milliliter (ml); and (ii) purchase medicines only those found in Philippine National Drug Formulary (PNDF); and;

Municipal Health Officer maintain the following: (i.) Stocks Inventory Report which shows the quantity of medicines received from the Municipality, the complete description of medicines received, the quantity of medicines utilized within a month, and balance of medicines in quantity per item at the end of the month; (ii.) Utilization Report which shows the complete name of patient, date of visit, complete address, age, gender, heath complaints of patient, diagnosis, complete description and quantity of dispensed medicines; (iii.) Monthly Summary of Medicines Utilized which shows the quantity of medicines dispensed to patients taken from Utilization Report and complete description of medicines; and iv. Annual Inventory Report which shows the quantity of medicines remained in stocks as of year-end and complete description of per items of medicines.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:
Municipal Budget Officer to fully accomplish all entries in the Obligation Requests (ObR) and regularly update the RAAO to facilitate the preparation of monthly list of signed and issued Obligation Requests with information such as ObR control number, name of payee, particulars/nature of transaction, amount, Function/Program/ Project (FPP), complete budget name, name of responsibility center, date signed and account code, for submission to the Audit Team Leader for audit and monitoring purposes;

Acting Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursement vouchers for processing and payment are supported with duly accomplished Obligation Request such as FPP per approved appropriation, account code, control number assigned to the ObR, responsibility center, and signature of Municipal Budget Officer (MBO) on the certification of existence of available appropriation portion of ObR;

Municipal Treasurer to ensure that claims for payment are duly supported with the necessary documents, including the duly accomplished ObR and the signature of the Municipal Budget Officer to establish their regularity; and
Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to support and coordinate with each other in the preparation of the complete Registries of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) and Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances (SAAOB) for CY 2016 to be used in the presentation of Statement of Comparative Budget and Actual Amount in the CY 2016 Financial Statements, and every accounting period thereafter.

We recommended that the:
General Services Officer prepare and submit the complete Report on the Physical Count of PPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records; and (ii) maintain Property Cards for all PPE accounts per category;
Municipal Accountant maintain (i) Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) for all PPE accounts per category; (ii) reconcile the PPELCs with the PPE General Ledger accounts, especially the Motor Vehicle account; and (iii) account for the specific lots comprising the year-end balance of the Land account and recognize all unrecorded real properties  owned by the Municipality in the accounting books as soon as titles or evidence of ownership are transferred in the name of the Municipality;

Municipal Treasurer exert all efforts to locate documents needed to transfer titles in the name of the Municipality;

Municipal Budget Officer set aside budget for the expenses necessary for the transferring of titles in the name of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the:
Acting Human Resource Management Officer to hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months in order to limit the expenditures on programs that are highly essential to merit the recruitment of these personnel and avoid exceeding the 45% Personal Services Limitation; 

Municipal Accountant to support disbursements of funds for services rendered by job order personnel with accomplishment reports to establish validity and propriety of payment and record the payroll of job order and casual personnel in Salaries and Wages - Casual/Contractual account instead of Other General Services account for fair presentation of financial statements;

Acting HRMO to require the job order personnel to prepare and submit monthly accomplishment reports pursuant to Paragraph 4.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001; and

Municipal Budget Officer to (a) submit a written explanation (i) on charging the payroll of job order and casual personnel to the budget for Provision for Personnel Development Program and Integrated Rural Development Projects and Services without prior approval from Sanggunian Bayan considering that these budgets have vague or broad description on how to spend the funds, (ii) on how and where the ₱10.8 million excess payroll of job order and casual personnel was taken from the Municipal Budget; and (b) to increase the Personal Services budget to accommodate the payroll of job order and casual personnel in the next budget preparation but not to exceed the 45% Personal Services Limitation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal officials and employees concerned to:
abide strictly with the COA regulations on the use of motor vehicles and refrain from utilizing government funds for gasoline consumption of privately owned vehicles;

indicate the plate number and the specific purpose of travel in the trip tickets;

exert effort to save funds under capital outlay and appropriate for the acquisition of brand new service vehicles in the succeeding budget year;

require the refund of all gasoline reimbursements amounting to ₱219,066.64 made by officials receiving fixed transportation allowance.

We recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive (i) prioritize the placement of a full-time MDRRM Officer to focus on core functions of the MDRRMO and the three mandatory staff personnel at the MDRRMO to handle the administration and training, research and planning, and operations and warning to effectively and efficiently address the requirements of the above-cited existing rules and regulations on disaster preparedness, mitigation, recovery and response;

MPDO fast track the preparation of the Municipality’s Comprehensive Development Plan (CDP), Comprehensive Land-Use Plan (CLUP) and Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Plan (MDRRMP) in order that disaster risk management activities could be integrated to the development plan of the Municipality to prevent further loss of lives and properties; 

Municipal Budget Officer maintain a separate Registry of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations for LDRRMF pursuant to Item 5.1.4 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 so that the Audit Team could verify the accuracy of utilization report.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and ECMUH
address urgently the issues surrounding the non-completion of the Municipality’s 10-year solid waste management plan to pave the way for its completion and subsequent endorsement for approval to the National Solid Waste Management Commission; 

involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household and business level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality;

seek the help of private companies/organizations in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste;

formulate solid waste management programs that would encourage and motivate the public to give their cooperation and full support.

We recommended that the 
GAD Focal Point/Person, who is also the Municipal Budget Officer, provide 5% of the total budget for the accomplishment of Gender and Development (GAD) programs/ projects/ activities (PPAs); 

require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (CPDO) to install a computerized system for the establishment of the GAD database in time for the next GAD Plan and Budget preparation.

We recommended that the 

(a) Municipal Engineer and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) ensure strict compliance with 

(i) Section 62 of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 requiring the issuance of Certificate of Acceptance to contractor one year from project completion and upon submission of the warranty security by the contractor;

(ii) Sections 6.1 and 6.2 of Annex “E” of  the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 requiring 10% retention on payments to contractor to cover for possible uncorrected discovered defects and third party liabilities; 

(iii) Sections 37.2.1 and 39.1 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 requiring the contractor to post performance security upon contract signing to guarantee his faithful performance of his obligations under the contract; 

(iv) DOLE DO No. 13, Series of 1998 on the submission of construction safety and health program duly approved by DOLE; and 

(v) DPWH Department Order No. 216 on the submission of copy of Diary or Log and photographic records with imprinted dates; 


(b) Municipal Accountant, Municipal Engineer and BAC  submit the lacking documents as required by COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 12, 2012 and Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; 


(c)  Municipal Engineer conduct thorough review on the computation of ABC to ensure its compliance with the prescribed rules and regulations specifically on Department Order No. 22, series 2015 dated February 18, 2015 before the same is submitted to the Office of the Municipal Mayor for approval.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the 

(a) Acting Human Resource Management Officer to 

(i) hire job order personnel based on necessity and skills/competencies and who should be identified/attributed to specific local projects authorized by the Sanggunian for a period not exceeding six months; and 

(ii) prepare and issue policy guidelines on the necessity and qualifications of the individuals to be hired under job orders pursuant to Section 2, Rule XI of the Revised Omnibus Rules Implementing Book V of Executive (EO) No. 292, in order to limit the expenditures on programs that are highly essential to merit the recruitment of these personnel; 

(b) City Accountant to support disbursements of funds for services rendered by job order personnel with accomplishment reports to establish validity and propriety of payment; 

(c) Acting HRMO to require the job order personnel to prepare and submit monthly accomplishment reports pursuant to Paragraph 4.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that the 

(a) Municipal Budget Officer  fully accomplish all entries in the Obligation Requests (ObR) and regularly update the RAAO to facilitate the preparation of monthly list of signed and issued Obligation Requests with information such as ObR control number, name of payee, particulars/nature of transaction, amount, Function/Program/Project (FPP), complete budget name, name of responsibility center, date signed and account code, for submission to the to the Audit Team Leader for audit and monitoring purposes; 


(b) Municipal Accountant ensure that disbursement vouchers for processing and payment are supported with duly accomplished Obligation Request such as FPP per approved appropriation, account code, control number assigned to the ObR, responsibility center, and signature of Municipal Budget Officer (MBO) on the certification of existence of available appropriation portion of ObR; 

(c) Municipal Treasurer ensure that claims for payment are duly supported with the necessary documents, including the duly accomplished ObR and the signature of the Municipal Budget Officer to establish their regularity; and 

(d) Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant help and coordinate with each other in the preparation of the complete Registries of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAO) and Statement of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances (SAAOB) for CY 2015 to be used in the presentation of Statement of Comparative Budget and Actual Amount in the CY 2015 Financial Statements, and every accounting period thereafter.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive and MENRO 

(a) address urgently the issues surrounding the non-completion of the Municipality’s 10-year solid waste management plan to pave the way for its completion and subsequent endorsement for approval to the National Solid Waste Management Commission; 

(b) involve closely the Barangay officials and civic leaders in the strict implementation on the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign at the household and business level on the ordinances issued by the Municipality; 

(c) seek the help of private companies/ organizations in the conduct of a more aggressive and intensive information campaign on the proper segregation of waste;  and

(d) formulate solid waste management programs that would encourage and motivate the public to give their cooperation and full support.

We recommended that the 

(a) Municipal Accountant  

(i) strictly comply with the regulation on the rendition of accounts and financial reports in order not to delay the verification and audit of transactions; 

(ii) observe the due dates in the submission to the Audit Team of the required financial reports and documents;  

(iii) submit the 20 disbursement vouchers amounting to ₱2,269,506.46 to avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension;  


(b) top management 

(i) augment the manpower complement of the Accounting Department through, as far as practicable, reassignment from other departments of personnel with relevant competencies; 

(ii) enjoin all officers and offices concerned to comply with the submission of adequate documents before forwarding any claim to the Accounting Department for processing.
